===Etymology 1===
{{wikipedia}}
From {{inh|en|enm|ponnen}}, {{m|enm|ponen}}, {{m|enm|punen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|punian}}, {{m|ang|pūnian||to [[pound#Verb|pound]], [[beat#Verb|beat]], [[bray]], [[bruise#Verb|bruise]], [[crush#Verb|crush]], [[grind#Verb|grind]]}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*punōną||to break to pieces, [[pulverize]]}}. See {{m|en|pound}}. As a kind of word play, from the notion of "beating" the words into place.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[beat#Verb|beat]]; [[strike#Verb|strike]] with [[force#Noun|force]]; to [[ram#Verb|ram]]; to [[pound#Verb|pound]], as in a [[mortar]]; reduce to [[powder#Noun|powder]], to [[pulverize]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Troilus|II|i|passage=He would '''pun''' thee into shivers with his fist.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To make or tell a pun; to make a [[play on words]].
#: {{ux|en|We '''punned''' about the topic until all around us groaned.}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[joke#Noun|joke]] or type of [[wordplay]] in which similar definitions or sounds of two words or phrases, or different definitions of the same word, are deliberately [[confuse]]d.
#:{{syn|en|paronomasia|play on words}}
#: {{hyper|en|joke}}
#: {{hypo|en|antanaclasis}}
#*{{RQ:Austen Mansfield Park|chapter=VI|volume=I|page=124|passage="Certainly, my home at my uncle's brought me acquainted with a circle of admirals. Of ''Rears'', and ''Vices'', I saw enough. Now do not be suspecting me of a '''pun''', I entreat."}}
